FG-71 — One-Page Timeline (Dates • Event • Pin • Effect)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Time tells the story better than adjectives.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: A four-column one-pager: Date • Event • Pin (Dkt/Ex/Tr) • Effect. Use it in your brief, appendix, and OA packet.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft 8–12 rows for your case; add to the appendix front.
	•	✅ Model Response: “07/31 — USPS receipt — Ex A:1 — Timely.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: A clean timeline is a credibility engine.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A single-row calendar with pins in the margin.

⸻

FG-72 — Dual Relief Menu (Decide Now / Remand Narrow)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Offer two doors: summary relief and limited remand.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One-sentence summary line; one-sentence remand block (task/time/scope/fallback). Keep both neutral.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write and paste a two-line menu at your conclusion.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Reverse (wrong test). Alternatively, remand 21 days for findings (a)–(d); 20-min harm hearing.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Choices win signatures.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two buttons (“Decide” / “Remand”) flowing to a signature strip.

⸻

FG-73 — One-Pin Proof (Anchor Every Paragraph)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Every argument paragraph gets one anchor pin.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Tie each paragraph’s thesis to a single Dkt/Ex/Tr pin. Overpins clutter; no pins float.
	•	📝 Assignment: Annotate five paragraphs with one anchor pin each.
	•	✅ Model Response: “The court skipped harm (Dkt 18 at 2).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: One anchor beats a citation storm.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Paragraphs with a single anchor icon in the margin.

⸻

FG-74 — Quote Block Hygiene (Exact Line • Pin • Brackets)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Quotes are scalpels—use them precisely.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Exact lines + pin; use [brackets] for grammar; ellipses sparingly; no stitched quotes.
	•	📝 Assignment: Rewrite one quote block with exact pin and bracket fixes.
	•	✅ Model Response: “The court ‘did not reach’ factor (b).” (Dkt 18 at 2).
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Surgical quotes build trust.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A scalpel icon trimming a quote ribbon.

⸻

FG-75 — Tight Headings (Answer, Don’t Ask)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Headings should answer the question in ≤12 words.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Convert interrogatives to answers; front-load verbs; mirror SoR; avoid adjectives.
	•	📝 Assignment: Rewrite three headings to answer the question directly.
	•	✅ Model Response: “The court erred by denying relief without harm findings.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Headings are your closing argument in bold.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A bold heading tile with a small checkmark.

⸻

FG-76 — Record-Only Relief (No New Facts)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Ask for outcomes you can prove from the existing record.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: If you need facts, offer limited remand; don’t smuggle in new evidence via 28(j).
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a relief paragraph based only on Dkt/Ex/Tr pins.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Reverse (wrong test) or limited remand for findings on (a)–(d); pins: Dkt 18:2; Ex A:1.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Records win; rumors sink.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A door labeled “Record” with an open sign.

⸻

FG-77 — Short Authority Letters (Fit, Not Flourish)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: New authority gets fit + pin, not re-argument.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: ≤180 words: holding line; how it maps to your issue; one or two pins; “no new facts” line.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write a 150-word 28(j) letter with a single relief line.
	•	✅ Model Response: “[Case] confirms factor-finding requirement; Issue 1 here turns on missing harm findings (Dkt 18:2; Ex A:1).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Fit is the whole job.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small envelope pointing into a pin tag.

⸻

FG-78 — Friendly Clarify Motion (Fix the Lens)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A narrow clarify motion can rescue a misread without provoking defense.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Quote the misread line; show the pin; propose one-line correction; no rhetoric; no schedule change.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 6-line clarify motion correcting “harm reached” → “not reached.”
	•	✅ Model Response: “Clarify p.12 n.3 to ‘not reached’; record: Dkt 18 at 2; no schedule change.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Fix the lens, then the view.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A camera focus ring snapping into clarity.

⸻

FG-79 — Data One-Pager (Counts • Dates • Sources)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Tables convince faster than paragraphs.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Show counts/dates; cite official sources; include a capture date and hash; RJN if needed.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 1-page table with 6 rows from official dockets.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Days pending by motion (official dockets, captured 08/19; SHA-256 …).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Numbers cut through narrative.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A simple table with a tiny fingerprint.

⸻

FG-80 — Procedural Mercy (Ask for Less, Get More)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Offering narrow relief signals credibility and often wins broader outcomes.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Propose smaller steps (clarify one footnote; limited remand; admin stay 72h) instead of grand relief.
	•	📝 Assignment: Replace a “big ask” with a narrow one in 2 lines.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Clarify p.12 n.3 (‘not reached’) or limited remand for findings on harm; 21 days.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Narrow mercy beats broad ambition.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small, signable order card with a green check.